      "question": "Find the roots of the quadratic equation $x^2 - (\\sqrt{3} + 1)x + \\sqrt{3} = 0$ by the factorisation method.",
      "answer": "$x = \\sqrt{3}, x = 1$",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Express the middle term $ -(\\sqrt{3} + 1)x $ as $ -\\sqrt{3}x - x $ to factorise by grouping.",
          "Factorise the expression $ x(x - \\sqrt{3}) - 1(x - \\sqrt{3}) = 0 $ to find the roots."
        ],
        "derivation": "$x^2 - \\sqrt{3}x - x + \\sqrt{3} = 0 \\\\ x(x - \\sqrt{3}) - 1(x - \\sqrt{3}) = 0 \\\\ (x - \\sqrt{3})(x - 1) = 0 \\\\ x - \\sqrt{3} = 0 \\text{ or } x - 1 = 0 \\\\ x = \\sqrt{3}, x = 1$"
      },
